# Help output

The brief help output should document CLI options only.

    :$ sesh -h (exit: 0)

```stdout
Usage: sesh [OPTIONS]

Options:
  -h                   Print brief help
      --help           Print complete help
      --config <PATH>  Path to a custom config file
  -q, --query <STR>    Seed the initial query
  -1, --select-1       Automatically switch when the initial query has only one match
  -0, --exit-0         Exit without opening the UI if the initial query has no matches
  -f, --filter         Filter non-interactively using the initial query
  -r, --repo <GLOB>    Additional repository globs to surface alongside existing tmux sessions
  -V, --version        Print version
```

The complete help output should include detailed key binding and configuration sections.

    :$ sesh --help (exit: 0)

```stdout
Usage: sesh [OPTIONS]

Options:
  -h
          Print brief help

      --help
          Print complete help

      --config <PATH>
          Path to a custom config file. When omitted, sesh reads $XDG_CONFIG_HOME/sesh/sesh.toml, or
          ~/.config/sesh/sesh.toml when $XDG_CONFIG_HOME is unset.

  -q, --query <STR>
          Seed the initial query

  -1, --select-1
          Automatically switch when the initial query has only one match

  -0, --exit-0
          Exit without opening the UI if the initial query has no matches

  -f, --filter
          Filter non-interactively using the initial query

  -r, --repo <GLOB>
          Additional repository globs to surface alongside existing tmux sessions. Pass once per
          glob; these stack with repo.globs from config, and each matching jj repo can be used as
          context for new repo-backed workspaces. A leading ~ path component expands to the user's
          home directory.

  -V, --version
          Print version

Key bindings:
  C-d               Delete the repository and close the session.
  C-f               Flag or unflag a live session.
  C-n               Create the session without switching to it.
  C-o               Open or cancel the onto revision picker.
  C-p               Toggle the preview pane outside onto mode.
  C-r, M-r          Set or reset the current repo.
  C-u               Clear the filter.
  C-x               Close a live session.
  C-y               Confirm a pending deletion.
  up, down          Move selection by one row.
  C-k, C-j          Move selection by one row.
  M-up, M-down      Move selection to the first or last row.
  M-k, M-j          Move selection to the first or last row.
  S-up, S-down      Scroll the preview pane up or down.
  tab, S-tab        Jump between fuzzy matches in onto mode.
  enter             Accept the onto revision, or switch to the session, creating
                    it if necessary.
  esc, C-g, C-c     Cancel onto mode, or close the UI.

Configuration:
  The config file is TOML. It is optional; when no file is present, sesh uses
  the built-in defaults.

  repo.globs        Glob patterns for jj repositories to surface alongside
                    existing tmux sessions. These stack with any --repo command-
                    line globs. A leading ~ path component expands to the user's
                    home directory.
  tmux.setup        Shell script to run after sesh creates a detached tmux
                    session. The script runs in the new session's tmux context
                    and working directory, so commands can use default tmux
                    targets and relative paths.
  ui.sigil          Character used to mark live tmux sessions in the picker.

Example:
  Below is an example configuration that makes use of every available
  configuration field.

  [repo]
  globs = [
    "~/Code/*",
    "~/.config/nvim"
  ]

  [tmux]
  setup = '''
  tmux rename-window shell
  tmux new-window -n editor 'nvim .'
  '''

  [ui]
  sigil = "●"

```

